2026-06-17 16:04:34 | DEBUG    | openai._base_client  | Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/deployments/text-embedding-3-small/embeddings', 'headers': {'api-key': '<redacted>'}, 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-6103f980-f572-4600-bfd5-dc08fea7bb55', 'post_parser': <function Embeddings.create.<locals>.parser at 0x0000020C367D9BC0>, 'security': {'bearer_auth': True}, 'content': None, 'json_data': {'input': ['6 (c) The relation between V and I is not unique, i.e., there is more than one value of V for the same current I, figure.', '7.', 'COLOUR CODE FOR CARBON RESISTORS The colour code for carbon resistance is given in the following table.', 'Colour code of carbon resistors Colour Letter as No.', 'Mulitplier Colour Tolerance anAid to memory Black B 0 10 0 Gold 5% Brown B 1 10 1 Silver 10% Red R 2 10 2 No colour 20% Orange O 3 10 3 Yellow Y 4 10 4 Green 5 10 5 Blue B 6 10 6 Violet V 7 10 7 Grey 8 10 8 White W 9 10 9 Gold 10 –1 Silver 10 –2 To remember the value of colour coding used for carbon resistor, the following sentences are found to be of great help (where bold letters stand for colours).', 'B B ROY Green, Britain Very Good Wife Gold Silver.', 'Way of finding the resistance of carbon resistor from its colour coding.', 'In the system of colour coding, Strips of different colours are given on the body of the resistor, figure.', 'The colours on strips are noted from left to right.', '(i) Colour of the first stip A from the end indicates the first significant figure of resistance in ohm.', '(ii) Colour of the second strip B indicate the second significant figure of resistance in ohm.', '(iii) The colour of the third strip C indicates the multiplier, i.e., the number of zeros that will follow after the two significant figure.', '(iv) The colour of fourth strip R indicates the tolerance limit of the resistance value of percentage accuracy of resistance.', '8.', 'COMBINATION OF RESISTORS 8.1 Resistances in Series Resistors are said to be connected in series, if the same current is flowing through each resistor when some poential difference is applied across the combination.', '1.', 'Let V be the potential difference applied across A and B using the battery \x1f.', 'In series combination, the same current (say I) will be passing through each resistance.', '2.', 'Let V1, V2, V3 be the potential difference across R1, R2 and R3 respectively.', 'According to Ohm’s law V1 = IR1, V2 = IR2, V3 = IR3 3.', 'Here, V = V1 + V2 + V3 = IR1 + IR2 + IR3 = I (R1 + R2 + R3) JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev.', 'Notes Class 12 Physics Chapter-2'], 'model': 'text-embedding-3-small', 'encoding_format': 'base64'}}
