mory note A balance point is obtained on the potentiometer wire if the fall of potential along the potentiometer wire, due to driving cell is greater than the e.m.f. of the cells to be balanced. 12.10 Determination of Internal Resistance of a Cell by Potentiometer Method To find the internal resistance r of a cell of emf \x1f using potentiometer, set up the circuit as shown in figure. JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev. Notes Class 12 Physics Chapter-2', '17 Close key K and maintain suitable constant current in the potentiometer wire with the help of rheostat Rh. Adjust the position of jockey on the potentiometer wire where if pressed, the galvanometer show no deflection. Let it be when jockey is as J1. Note the length AJ1 (= l1) of the potentiometer wire. Now emf of the cell, \x1f = potential difference across the length l1 of the potentiometer wire. or = Kl1 ...(1) where K is the potential gradient across the wire. Close key K1 and take out suitable resistance R from the resistance box in the cell circuit. Again find the position of the jockey on the potentiometer wire where galvanometer shows no deflection. Let it be at J2. Note the length of the wire AJ2 ( = l2 say). As current is being drawn from the cell, its terminal potential difference V is balanced and not emf . Therefore, potential difference between two poles of the cell, V = potential difference across the length l2 of the potentiometer wire i.e.   V = Kl2 ...(2) Dividing (1)', 'the wire AJ2 ( = l2 say). As current is being drawn from the cell, its terminal potential difference V is balanced and not emf . Therefore, potential difference between two poles of the cell, V = potential difference across the length l2 of the potentiometer wire i.e.   V = Kl2 ...(2) Dividing (1) by (2), we have 1 2 V \x01 \x02 \x02 ...(3) We know that the internal resistance r of a cell of emf \x1f, when a resistance R is connected in its circuit is given by V r R 1 R V V \x03 \x05 \x06 \x01 \x18 