 in the circuit. \x08 Electric energy, W = VIt = P.t \x08 Electric energy = electric power × time SI unit of electric energy is joule, wherre 1 joule = 1 volt × 1 ampere × 1 second = 1 watt × 1 second The commercial unit of electric en', 'an electric circuit for a given time is called electric energy consumed in the circuit. \x08 Electric energy, W = VIt = P.t \x08 Electric energy = electric power × time SI unit of electric energy is joule, wherre 1 joule = 1 volt × 1 ampere × 1 second = 1 watt × 1 second The commercial unit of electric energy is called a kilowatt- hour (kWh) or Board to Trade Unit (BOT) or UNIT of Electricity, in brief, where 1 kWh = 1 kilo watt × 1 hour = 1000 watt × 1 hour Thus 1 kilo watt hour is the total electric energy consumed when an electrical appliance of power 1 kilo-watt works for one hours. 1 kWh = 1000 Wh = (1000 W) × (60 × 60 s) = 3.6 × 10 6 J. Note that the number of units of electricity consumed = No. of kWh = watt hour 1000 \x04 2 2 Electric energy VI t I Rt V t / R \x02 \x02 \x02 13.3 Electricity Consumption (1) The price of electricity consumed is calculated on the basis of electrical energy and not on the basis of electrical power. (2) The unit Joule for energy is very small hence a big practical un', 'No. of kWh = watt hour 1000 \x04 2 2 Electric energy VI t I Rt V t / R \x02 \x02 \x02 13.3 Electricity Consumption (1) The price of electricity consumed is calculated on the basis of electrical energy and not on the basis of electrical power. (2) The unit Joule for energy is very small hence a big practical unit is considered known as kilowatt hour (KWH) or board of trade unit (B.T.U.) or simple unit. (3) 1 KWH or 1 unit is the quantity of electrical energy which dissipates in one hour in an electrical circuit when the electrical power in the circuit is 1 KWH thus 1 KWH = 1000 W \x04 3600 sec = 3.6 \x04 106 J. JEE | NEET | Class 8 - 10 Download eSaral App www.esaral.com Rev. Notes Class 12 Physics Chapter-2', '20 (4) Important formulae to calculate the no. of consumed units is Total watt Total hours n 1000 \x18 \x01 13.4  Combination of Bulbs (or Electrical Appliances) Bulbs (Heater etc.) Bulbs (Heater etc.) are in series are in parallel (1)Total power consumed (1) Total power consumed total 1 2 1 1 1 .... P P P \x01 \x02 \x02 Ptotal = P1 + P2 + P3 .... + Pn (2)In ‘n’ bulbs are identical, (2) If ‘n’ identical bulbs are total P P N \x01 in parallel. Ptotal = nP consumed P Brightness consumed P Brightness rated 1 V R P \x0e \x0e \x0e R 1 P i R \x0e \x0e \x0e i.e. in series combination i.e. in parallel combination bulb of lesser wattage will bulb of greater wattage will give more bright light and give more bright light and p.d. appeared across it will more current will pass be more. through it. Some Standard Cases for Series and Parallel Combination (1) If n identical bulbs first connected in series so S P P n \x01 and then connected in parallel. So PP = nP hence 2 P S P n P \x01 (2) An electric kettle has two coils when one coil is sw', 'd across it will more current will pass be more. through it. Some Standard Cases for Series and Parallel Combination (1) If n identical bulbs first connected in series so S P P n \x01 and then connected in parallel. So PP = nP hence 2 P S P n P \x01 (2) An electric kettle has two coils when one coil is switched on it takes time t1 to boil water and when the second coil is switched on it takes time t2 to boil the same water. If they are connected If they are connected in series in parallel S 1 2 1 1 1 P P P \x01 \x02 PP = P1 + P2 S S 1 1 2 2 1 1 1 H / t H /t H / t \x01 \x02 P 1 2 p 1 2 H H H t t t \x01 \x02 \x03HS=H1= H2 \x03 Hp = H1 = H2 so ts = t1+ t2 so p 1 2 1 1 1 t t t \x01 \x02 i.e. time taken by i.e. time taken by parallel combinationto boil the combination to boil the same quantity of water same quantity of water ts = t1 + t2 1 2 p 1 2 t t t t t \x01 \x02 (3) If three identical bulbs are connected in series as shown in figure then on closing the switch